        'DEFINITION: Basic strategy is a mathematically proven set of optimal playing decisions for every possible player hand vs dealer up-card combination, minimizing the house edge to approximately 0.5-1.0%.',
        'DETAILED RULES: Basic strategy covers 340+ specific decision points (all player hands vs all dealer up-cards). Decisions: Hit, Stand, Double, Split, Surrender. Varies by rules (S17 vs H17, DAS vs no DAS, number of decks). Published in 1956 by four US Army engineers (Baldwin, Cantey, Maisel, McDermott). Refined by computer analysis in the 1960s (Julian Braun, IBM).',
        'NUMBERS: House edge with basic strategy: 6-deck S17 DAS = 0.64% house edge. 6-deck H17 DAS = 0.86% house edge. 2-deck S17 DAS = 0.46% house edge. 1-deck S17 = 0.16% house edge. Single-deck 6:5 BJ = 1.55% house edge (worse than 8-deck 3:2). Without basic strategy (typical player errors): house edge increases to 2.0-3.5%. Perfect basic strategy reduces player errors by approximately 95%.',
        'STRATEGIC MEANING: Basic strategy is the minimum requirement for any serious blackjack player. Without it, the player is donating money. Memorizing basic strategy takes 10-20 hours of study. Dealers use basic strategy to check for player errors. Casino advantage comes from deviations from basic strategy (both player errors and the inherent house edge).',
        'DEALER PROCEDURE: Dealers do not advise on basic strategy. If a player asks "What should I do?" the dealer must respond "That is your decision, sir/ma\'am." Dealers may call the floor if a player consistently makes obviously wrong decisions (potential card counter? No, counters play non-basic strategy at high counts). Dealers enforce hand signals for all decisions for camera verification.',
